<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880428-0048 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief: Loews Corp. </HL><SO> </SO><CO> LTR SLH </CO><IN> TNM </IN><TEXT>   Loews Corp.'s Lorillard Inc. subsidiary said it sold its chewing tobacco and small-cigar brands to National Tobacco Co. for about $67.5 million.    National Tobacco is a limited partnership formed specifically to buy the Lorillard brands. Its majority owner is Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. The president of National Tobacco is Thomas Helms, formerly president of Helme Tobacco Co., which was sold in 1986 by Culbro Corp. to American Maize-Products Co.    Among the brands included in the sale are Beech-Nut and Beech-Nut Wintergreen smokeless tobacco, in addition to Between the Acts and Omega cigars. Also included is a Louisville, Ky., manufacturing facility and storage facilities in Wisconsin.    Lorillard said the sale will permit it to concentrate on its cigarette business, which includes the brands Newport, Kent and True.    In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares of Loews closed at $70, up $1.625. </TEXT></DOC>